title: Study of excitation functions and insights into the reaction mechanisms of 6Li fusion in Cu

Self-supporting natural Cu foils (1.7 - 2.5 mg/cm2,
99.99% pure) and Al-foils of thickness 2.3 mg/cm2
were prepared by properly rolling technique.
Both Cu and Al foils (0.5 mm thickness) were mounted on
aluminum rings of 12 mm and 22 mm inner and outer
diameter, respectively.
A pre-calibrated detector coupled with PC
operating with GENIE-2K software used to record the
spectra.
The energy resolution of the detector was <= 2.0 keV
at 1332 keV gamma rays of 60Co.
A total of four Cu-Al stacks, each of
which contained three Cu foils backed by Al, were
irradiated by varying the incident energy of 6Li3+
ions.
The total dose of each irradiation was
measured (average total dose ~538 uC) by an electron-
suppressed Faraday cup placed behind the target
assembly.
The uncertainties considered in the
cross-section measurement are:
- estimation of beam energy due to the degradation of
energy.
- energy straggling effects are expected to be small.
geometry-dependent efficiency of the
detector ( <= 2%)
target thickness (2%)
beam flux due to fluctuation in beam current
cross-section measurement from the
counting statics, deadtime (<10%)
